{"id":"project-LICHEN-l3w1","title":"oscore_protect_response missing NULL check for request_piv","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/oscore/oscore.c
Lines: 1790-1791

The oscore_protect_response function checks `request_piv_len > 0 && request_piv == NULL` which is correct, but compute_nonce is called unconditionally with request_piv:

```c
/* Response uses request's PIV for nonce */
compute_nonce(ctx->recipient_id, ctx->recipient_id_len,
              request_piv, request_piv_len, ctx->common_iv, nonce);
```

If request_piv_len is 0 but request_piv is NULL, compute_nonce handles this correctly (it checks piv_len > 0 before accessing). However, the parameter contract is unclear.

Looking at compute_nonce:
```c
if (piv_len > 0 && piv_len <= 5) {
    size_t piv_start = OSCORE_NONCE_LEN - piv_len;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < piv_len; i++) {
        nonce[piv_start + i] ^= piv[i];
    }
}
```

This is actually safe when piv_len == 0 because the loop doesn't execute. But the function should document that piv can be NULL when piv_len == 0.

